description.header: Project: Design a bracket used to make a simple coffee table
description.text:
Objectives:
To create a simple 3D part used to join wood parts in interesting ways.
To make the part strong enough to make a small coffee table. Audiences:
Mostly for G10+ students and product designers in Design Technology classes Preparation:
Students should study angles and sketch out their basic idea to work out lengths and heights. Also they should consider the wood sections they will use as legs. Steps: Firstly a triangular prism is drawn on CAD software, we used autodesk inventor. Then flaps are added in a 'fan' shape to the correct lengths depending on the wood chosen. Holes are then added with carefully measured countersunk sections for the screws you've chosen. The arrangement must be one hole per corner (diagonal) as otherwise the wood parts will get in the way of screwing the screws in! STL file generated and printed. Results:
This part at 45 degree angle should work fine (all thicknesses are 2mm and material is ABS). These factors could vary and students could experiment the strength of the part by loading weight on the top once the legs are added to see how much weight it could hold.

description.text:
Updated to include 4 1mm thick pads.  Seem to work just as well, taking less time to print.
Here are some pads I designed for reducing warping.  They are designed to snap off after printing.  Note, the pad is designed to fit on a square corner, which is where most warping happens.  Simply position the pad at the corners of your part, print and snap them off.  A little sanding will neaten things up after removal.  I have found them to work very well, as seen in the before and after photos.
Comments are welcome.

Finally - successful abs print without Warping! I have been trying all the methods that people recommend for printing ABS without warping including ABS acetone juice, blue tape/on glass, hairspray (2 kinds) as well as anti warping corner pads like those in this thing. I have finally had success using the following:
Bed Temp 110 degrees throughout print.
TWO GOOD COATS OF TRESemme Tres Two #5 "freeze hold" HAIRSPRAY ON A HOT BED
make sure your first layer is squished well into the bed.
extruder 235C for first layer, 230C for the rest. THE MAIN REASON FOR SUCCESS HERE SEEMS TO BE THE TYPE OF HAIRSPRAY!

comments.text: If there is still a little warping after the pads try running the print without the cooling fan. Its made a huge difference with my more solid abs prints. Hairspray on the build plate helps too.

A turntable for your very own drink-dispensing robot, and a pedestal to put the scale and drinks on. These are the physical parts for my iZac drinkbot project, details of which you can find here: http://blog.notdot.net/2011/11/Introducing-iZac-the-Android-Bartender

• Cut the pedestal from a sheet of 3mm acrylic, slot it together, and glue.
    a) Make sure to put the servo in the servo holder part (with the servo slotting in from the top, not the bottom) before you assemble and glue everything.
    b) There are two ways the legs can go together; I recommend having one long leg on each corner, instead of 2 corners with 2 legs and 2 with none.
    c) A laser cuttable servo horn, and a piece of retaining plastic to hold it on the servo are included. Screw two M2 screws through the servo horn so they face upwards, and secure them with bolts; these will act to couple the servo with the platform.
    d) Place the lazy susan bearing on top of the completed pedestal, and secure it with four short M3 machine screws and bolts. The screw heads should be on the lazy susan side, with the bolts underneath the pedestal top. You may want to ensure the four screws for the other side are already inserted in the other side of the lazy susan bearing before you do this.
  • Cut the turntable top and mounting from another piece of acrylic. Assemble the mounting part and glue it together, but do not glue it to the turntable yet. Attach it to the lazy susan bearing on the pedestal, lining up the M2 scews from the servo horn with the slots in the mounting.
  • Fit one of the sides onto the pedestal and glue it in place.
  • Fit an adjacent side to the turntable so that the intersection of the sides forms a pinch valve mount. Insert the part of the modified pinch valve that fits the mounting, and glue everything in place.
  • Repeat steps 4 and 5 for the other 4 sides and 2 pinch valves.
  • Assemble the pinch valves around the part you already glued in place by following the instructions on the pinch valve page. Use machine screws and nuts to secure the valves; do not glue anything.
  • Attach the air pump to the bottom of the turntable platform with a screw. The mounting may require modification for the exact design of air pump you are using.
  • Fit the completed turntable onto the mounting and glue it into place if desired - it holds fairly well purely based on friction, however.
  • Cut out and assemble the drink holder / scale unit in the obvious fashion. Attach a load cell and arduino / shield as desired.

title: Folgertech Prusa i3 2020 X-Axis Upgrade Gen-2 (Openbuilds V-Slot Rail System)

description.text:
This is the Gen-2 version of my X-Axis upgrade to the Folgertech Prusa i3 2020 Variant, however it should work with any 2020 rail printer, and could be adapted to an all-thread framed printer with a few additional brackets. It replaces the cheap linear bearings and 8mm rods with an Openbuilds V-Slot Gantry and rail system. Noise reduction is huge with this upgrade, accuracy is increased and overall stiffness of the X-Axis is also increased. This system is up and running on my printer along with a few others (although there are a few variation in the assembly). This version of the upgrade can utilize various length of rail (with the V-7 mount). The X Stepper Motor is mounted on the X gantry and rides along with it. It is great fro a Bowden setup, but you might want to stick with Gen-1 for a direct drive extruder, although I am running DD with this setup and have seen no issues at all. Just keep in mind the gantry gets pretty heavy with two steppers attached to it. The V-8 mount added a brace to help stiffen the rail, it's a bit flimsy installed on V-7, however I am still running V-7. The V-8 mount will require the rail be cut to the proper length, as I have not cut mine done and printers may vary I suggest install the two mounts and measuring the required rail length prior to cutting it. I have also added the Gen-1 X-mount (V-6) to the list of things, it's by far the most robust of all the mounts, and if you're switching from Gen-1 to Gen-2 you can reuse the same mounts if you want. Gen-1 X-Axis: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1285301 As with Gen-1 I am not writing assembly instructions as it is pretty straight forward, I have provided a link to a Imgur Album showing detailed photos of the build. This is a work in progress so there are variations of the build (with-in the album) so please keep this in mind when looking through the photos. http://imgur.com/a/1mZXH The endstop mount comes in two version, one has a 2.3mm hole that needs to be tapped, the other has a 3mm thru and will require a 3mm nut. there are two optiond for attaching the belt to the X-mounts (both shown in photos). the easiest way is to use the stamped M5T-nuts from OB and simply pinch the belt under the screw, make sure you install the T-nut with the threaded protrusion pointing up so the belt can slip under it. This method will have to be used if you stick with or use the V-6 mounts. Method two uses the slots provided in the V-7 & V-8 mounts. Just pull the belt through, lay it over and install two M3 Screws and washer to secure. This also requires you tap the M3 screws holes. Direct Drive Mount for NEMA 17 Extruders http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1278168 E3d V6 Bowden Mount (w/Proximity Sensor) http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1288706 I have provided a BOM You can checkout before and after videos here: Bench Test: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qpn-rzMczIo Before: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t4HJPyrFLzk In this video the Y-Axis upgrade was installed, the grinding noise you hear is the X-Carraige. After: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mqzbo9MErIo There is also a Lead Screw Mount for a M5 Nut, this will allow the stock M5 nut and All Thread to be used in-lieu-of the M8 Lead Screws. Just insert the M5 nut into the bottom of the adapter and mount like any other Lead Screw Nut (make sure the M5 nut is on the bottom). I haven't printer or tested this adapter so please let me know how it works out. Edit: 4-9-2016 Added two lead screw nut adapters to use in-lieu-of the 8mm brass lead screw nut. 5mm plain nut (this file have been printed and fits great

This is a robot shaped dog poop bag holder, use it when you walk your dog and everyone will know how cool and fashionable you are. This model is designed for the cheap poop bag rolls I order from China, they are 7cm long and 3cm in diameter, you can scale the model up if your bag rolls are larger. Printing instructions There are two STL files, one for the holder itself and one for the lid. The robot: The body had built-in support so you shouldn't need to add support in your slicer, I printed it in PLA with 1.2mm shell thickness and no infill. The lid: The lid doesn't require any support or infill but you need to print it with a top/bottom shell thickness of more then 1mm so the sides are solid because ... The lid is the wrong size - on purpose. The lid must be a very tight fit, otherwise it would fall off, making it a perfect fit would depend too much on the printer calibration and even the brand of filament so I made it intentionally too wide - you need to sand off the sides until you can easily push it in and out but it doesn't move by itself. The raised part of the lid is too small because: 1. so it wouldn't interfere with the sanding and/or scaling and 2. it's on the bottom so who cares. This model was made in SketchUp Make, fixed in netfabb basic, fixed again in Microsoft 3D Builder and supports were added in Meshmixer. the robot in the picture was sliced with Cura and printed on a Robo3D R1+ Hope you enjoy walking your dog and you don't have to pick up too much poop.

An STL file describes a raw unstructured triangulated surface by the unit normal and vertices (ordered by the right-hand rule) of the triangles using a three-dimensional Cartesian coordinate system. STL coordinates must be positive numbers, there is no scale information, and the units are arbitrary.
An ASCII STL file begins with the line:
Line 1
solid name
where name is an optional string (though if name is omitted there must still be a space after solid). The file continues with any number of triangles, each represented as follows: Line 2 to n-1
facet normal ni nj nk
In both ASCII and binary versions of STL, the facet normal should be a unit vector pointing outwards from the solid object. In most software this may be set to (0,0,0) and the software will automatically calculate a normal based on the order of the triangle vertices using the 'right-hand rule'
outer loop
vertex v1x v1y v1z
vertex v2x v2y v2z
vertex v3x v3y v3z
endloop
endfacet
where each n or v is a floating point number in sign-mantissa 'e'-sign-exponent format, e.g., "-2.648000e-002". The file concludes with:

title: Lead Screw Anti-Backlash - Folgertech - Prusa i3

description.text:
This is an upgrade to the M8 2mm pitch (4 starts) lead screw setup for my Folgertech 2020 Prusa i3 Printer, but it can be implemented to any printer that uses a standard brass T-nut and lead screw. 
After a short time I realized my lead screw nuts were wearing out and had quite a bit of play in them, so I bought replacement. however, they were not much better, the machining and quality of  these inexpensive lead screws and nuts are not the best. So I designed this simple anti-backlash setup. Backlash can greatly effect quality, especially under certain circumstances, Z retracts, Auto Bed Leveling, basically anything that moves Z up and down during a print. this setup has eliminated all backlash in my printer.  
The setup is simply four lead screw nuts four long M3 screws and four springs. I believe the photos will explain the setup better than I can in text, just remember to leave some play in the longer screws, you DO NOT want those tight against the LS Nuts!!!  but please feel free to comment with any questions you might have!?!? 
I have added my M8 to M5 Lead Screw Nut adapter for those that want to use the standard FT M5 lead screws, just print four of them. I have not however tested this setup, so if you try it please let me know how it works out!?!?

comments.text: Have you had a problem with leadscrew binding?
comments.author: Wolfking1985

comments.text: I have not had binding issues at all. If you had free movement prior to installation you should still have it, the only difference might be a l very sight bit of added resistance. I think the key is to only apply enough force on the springs to take the play out of the system. On my printer I used a old set of LS nuts that were pretty worn for the upper nuts, and a new set for the lower, I set the tension pretty low and did apply some lubricant to the threads. It's been working like a champ for months :)

The idea is to be able to use it as a daylight tank. The parts :
  • the top : it is the cover with a hole for the handle and the liquid
  • the bottom : the tank itself. There is space for the film cassette and one for the film/liquid
  • the axle : the part where you stick your film and then the film got wound around it
  • the handle : to turn the axle
  • the film lock : missing you can probably use a paper clip or print something to keep the film in the axle
  • the locking tab : missing they are need to keep the top on the bottom. You may use a M3 screw to keep the tab on the bottom
    • How to use it :
  • You put an extremity of the film in the axle. Lock it in place with something (haven't really think about it ...could be anything like a paper clip).
  • Place the top on the bottom.
  • Secure the top with M3 screw (and a small tab)
  • Place the handle
  • Pour liquid in the tank
  • Turn the handle to unwind the film from the cassette to the tank
  • Develop like in a rondix
    • The main limitation I see are :
  • Very hard to pour liquid in it as the pouring hole is small
  • Could be leaky
  • not light tight (?)
    • I haven't tested it yet Any idea are welcome :)

The idea is to mimic the rondix 35. It started with the other project, but I was thinking it was too big. I wanted to put the film vertical instead of horizontal as I don't see why it wouldn't work.
Putting the film that was allows not to deal with a leak near the handle which was my main problem with the previous design.

title: Box for CL1-GSM mobile phone remote relay

description.text:
This is a box for a gsm remote relay to control a electric socket via SMS.
Don't mess about with high voltage if you don't know what you are doing.
It is very dangerous, you could get electrocuted or start a fire! I find it difficult to print this in ABS as it warps. I used PLA in 0.45mm layers and a 0.5mm nozzel. Use M3 nuts and bolts to assemble and a M6 eye bolt and lock nuts for a hook.
Use a 20x20x2mm plexiglass piece as window to see the status leds, or print a blind if you don't need it. Leaving it open may cause small animals and bugs to nest inside the box and cause fires. Use a spring loaded M3 bolt, capped with a M3 nylon spacer, to manually change switch status. Fix the controller to the inside of the lid. The pdf shows the lid outside down for easier printing. Drill holes for the cables to the sockets as needed. A 10A fuse to protect the relay is probably a good idea. Hole for a panel mounted glass fuse can be drilled beside the M6 hook on top.

title: Snug-down clip for TonnoPro Tonneau Cover

description.text: I purchased a TonnoPro Hard Fold Tonneau Cover for my truck. The rear clamps did a great job keeping the rear corner gaskets tight against the top edge of the tailgate but, across the top center of the tailgate, the cover would bow up a little causing a gap between the top of the tailgate and the bottom of the cover's gasket. Although probably not a big problem it did bother me. So I devised a way, using a bungee cord, to pull down on the center of the cover but needed a way to connect the bungee to the cover. I noticed the the framing of the cover was such that I could make a clip to set in the framing and then couple the bungee cord to it with either end of the bungee attached to a tie-down in the bed of the truck. It worked out great - it is quick and easy to use and is not obstructive to the cover itself - no holes to drill or alterations to make. One of the pics with the pencil shows the opening before I attached the clip - about 1/4" space - and the other shows no gap after attaching the clip. The other pics are of various viewpoints showing how the clip attached to the frame's C channel. Note that it prints upside down - I had to flip it over so that it would hook on the cover's frame.

description.text:
Based on the "Math Mixer" this math toy was designed to print in one piece and have complete functionality. the idea is simple take it in your hand roll it over it and start playing.
This star has 6 outer dices and one central dice. In the original game you are supposed to take the central dice number add the outer black dice number and start by adding, multiplying, subtracting and dividing each other number to get to that result, but we thought that's not the only way to play it in fact you could come up with your own set of rules.
As an example you could take the central dice as resulta and start by adding the outer numbers but you are forced to multiply by the biggest one at any given point so try and get the result by any math operation you know.

description.text:
EDIT 2: Hardware listed has only been tested by me for the 1.5" model. Any other model might require some fiddling, but since the stud size is given that should be no problem. EDIT: I have added various heights of the pedal spacer, as several users have asked for shorter spacers. The file Pedal_Spacer3.STL is the original, 1.5 inch thick spacer (The "3" is in the name because it is the 3rd revision), and the rest of the sizes have more descriptive names following "Pedal_Spacer". The new sizes are 1.25", 1", 0.75", 0.5". Enjoy. This part is a spacer for the accelerator pedal of a Ford Fiesta ST. As stock, the pedal sits about an inch and a half recessed from the brake and clutch pedal's plane, and this part, along with other hardware, brings the accelerator into the same plane. The advantage to this is less time spent switching between gas and brake, making cornering smother, it also seems to make the driver's seating more comfortable, but that's subjective. I created this project as a cheaper alternative to available kits, and tried to make it as comprehensive as possible. To install this you will need the following: Tools:
Metric socket set, including 12mm and 13mm sockets and extension
Flat head screwdriver (optional) Hardware:
M8 by 1-1/4 inch coupling nut
  • McMaster PN 90009A222
  • True Value PN 44768-B
    • M8 by 16mm bolt: I used a flange bolt if you do not, you may also want washers.
  • McMaster PN 95735A416
  • True Value PN 43338-B
    • You may also want a thread locker such a loctite or a spacer, I will explain below. IMPORTANT: Wear gloves for install. Ford didn't grind the brake pedal arm, so I cut my thumbs to ribbons during the install. Don't be like me, have intact thumbs! Installation Steps:
    1: Remove the two OEM nuts from accelerator pedal. The lower nut is easily visible and is on the left of the pedal. The upper nut is on the right and is harder to reach. There is a third nut that appears to hold the plate to the firewall and is much easier to see than the upper pedal nut. Do not be fooled! Get under there and take a good look. I think the OEM nuts use some sort of mechanical thread locking, so they take a little more torque to get off than you might expect. Use the 13mm socket and extension for this step. 2: With the nuts off, slide the pedal away from the firewall off of the threaded studs. The pedal will still be connected by its wires, but you should have enough room for the install. If not, the side of the connector facing away from the firewall has a clip, depress the clip with your thumb and wiggle the connector off of the pedal. I had to use a flat head screwdriver here to shim the gap between the male and female part of the connector to get them apart. They are SNUG. 3: Screw the coupling nuts on to the studs. Here would be where you would use the spacers and thread locker if you have them. I may do this in the future, and then I will provide a spacer part number as well. Test fit the spacer with the coupling washers; the washers should be just a bit recessed of their holes. 4: Put the spacer on over the coupling nuts. The end where the hole is closer to the bend goes up. 5: Put the pedal over the spacer and use the M8 bolts to affix the pedal to the spacer and coupling nuts. Reattach the plug if you detached it. Now you will likely need to readjust your seating, I did. At this time I know the part fits a Fiesta ST and am working toward confirmation of it fitting a Focus ST. I provided drawings if you would like to take it upon yourself to confirm: just print it out on paper, make sure the dimensions are accurate, and please let me know whether or not it fits! Thanks EDIT: Special thanks to Reddit's u/poco153 for providing the True Value part numbers. Check Poco's build out.
